In this module, we've seen
what ecological monitoring 

2
00:00:13,019 --> 00:00:16,332
a protected area means
and that it intends 

3
00:00:16,505 --> 00:00:20,480
to asses the state 
of the territory's values. 

4
00:00:20,685 --> 00:00:24,072
These values are characterized 
by ecological attributes 

5
00:00:24,296 --> 00:00:26,396
which are described by indicators. 

6
00:00:26,585 --> 00:00:28,747
Ecological monitoring 
follows a protocol 

7
00:00:28,951 --> 00:00:31,788
that specifies assembly plan 
and approach to use. 

8
00:00:31,994 --> 00:00:36,307
So, let's summarize the steps
to follow to implement 

9
00:00:36,529 --> 00:00:38,417
ecological monitoring. 

10
00:00:38,617 --> 00:00:41,654
First off, you need to identify
the values to monitor,

11
00:00:41,891 --> 00:00:44,841
the ones that matter to the 
management  of the protected area

12
00:00:45,064 --> 00:00:48,713
 and that could be part of a 
sensible ecological monitoring plan.

13
00:00:48,921 --> 00:00:52,283
It can be an animal species 
or an ecosystem 

14
00:00:52,477 --> 00:00:55,565
within the protected area,
for instance.

15
00:00:55,738 --> 00:00:58,663
You then determine 
the key ecological attributes. 

16
00:00:58,874 --> 00:01:02,025
The one that will characterize 
the value and help understand

17
00:01:02,182 --> 00:01:04,144
the state of the protected area,

18
00:01:04,341 --> 00:01:07,916
the density of the species 
that is being monitored for instance

19
00:01:08,111 --> 00:01:11,174
or it's population dynamics 

20
00:01:11,378 --> 00:01:16,615
or even original floral composition
of the chosen ecosystem. 

21
00:01:17,443 --> 00:01:20,443
It is generally useful 
to specify some indicators 

22
00:01:20,692 --> 00:01:24,605
easily measurable to express
these ecological attributes. 

23
00:01:25,284 --> 00:01:28,509
In other words, the number 
of individuals 

24
00:01:28,725 --> 00:01:31,988
of the targeted species, 
the age distribution, 

25
00:01:32,184 --> 00:01:35,934
or even the presence or absence 
of invasive species 

26
00:01:36,143 --> 00:01:38,431
within the ecosystem. 

27
00:01:39,566 --> 00:01:43,016
The next step consist of identifying
the acceptable limits 

28
00:01:43,191 --> 00:01:46,367
within which the 
ecological attributes may vary. 

29
00:01:47,362 --> 00:01:49,962
The limit between 
a healthy attribute and one 

30
00:01:50,144 --> 00:01:52,744
that requires intervention.

31
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:56,622
An example is to set the minimal 
number of individuals 

32
00:01:56,848 --> 00:02:01,123
that indicates the endangerment 
of the species or on the other hand,

33
00:02:01,336 --> 00:02:06,211
a maximum number that implies 
an excessive number of individuals 

34
00:02:06,379 --> 00:02:09,742
that puts the ecosystem at risk. 

35
00:02:11,086 --> 00:02:14,598
Then come the choice in method
to measure these indicators 

36
00:02:14,809 --> 00:02:16,885
which would of course 
take into account 

37
00:02:17,070 --> 00:02:19,395
the monetary values 
but also the capabilities 

38
00:02:19,592 --> 00:02:23,930
of the protected area itself 
in terms of means and skills.

39
00:02:25,398 --> 00:02:29,348
You can either choose to directly
count the animals 

40
00:02:29,556 --> 00:02:33,006
or indirectly by monitoring tracks 
for example,

41
